==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|μελαγχολία||[[atrabiliousness]]|tr=melancholia|lang=grc}}, from {{term|μέλας||tr=melas|lang=grc}}, {{term|μελαν-||black, dark, murky|tr=melan-|lang=grc}} + {{term|χολή||bile|tr=chole|lang=grc}}. Compare the Latin {{term/t|la|ātra bīlis||black bile}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈmelənkəli/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈmɛl.ənˌkɑl.i/}}
* {{audio|En-us-melancholy.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Affected with great [[sadness]] or [[depression]].
#: {{usex|lang=en|'''Melancholy''' people don't talk much.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1922|author={{w|Ben Travers}}|title={{w|A Cuckoo in the Nest}}
|chapter=1|url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1521052W
|passage=“[…] the awfully hearty sort of Christmas cards that people do send to other people that they don't know at all well. You know. The kind that have mottoes{{...}}. And then, when you see [the senders], you probably find that they are the most '''melancholy''' old folk with malignant diseases. […]”}}

